  "local_port": 50818,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm a rookie. How should I start preparing for getting selected in GSoC 17?",
  "response": "Getting selected for Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is a great goal! Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you prepare effectively for GSoC 17:\n\n### 1. Understand What GSoC Is\nGSoC is a global program focused on bringing more student developers into open source software development. Students work with an open source organization on a 3-month programming project during their break from school.\n\n### 2. Choose Your Programming Language\n- **Proficiency**: Ensure you are proficient in at least one programming language. Commonly used languages in GSoC include Python, Java, C++, and JavaScript.\n- **Practice**: If you are not confident, spend some time practicing on platforms like LeetCode, HackerRank, or Codecademy.\n\n### 3. Explore Organizations and Projects\n- **List of Organizations**: Check the list of organizations participating in GSoC 17. You can find this on the official GSoC website when the list is published.\n- **Interest and Skills**: Look for projects that align with your interests and skills. Start exploring their codebases, documentation, and past GSoC projects.\n\n### 4. Contribute to Open Source\n- **Start Small**: Begin with small contributions like fixing typos in documentation, reporting bugs, or asking questions in the community forums.\n- **Increase Complexity**: Gradually move on to more complex contributions like fixing bugs or implementing small features.\n- **Communication**: Engage with the community through mailing lists, IRC, or other communication platforms used by the organization.\n\n### 5. Learn Version Control\n- **Git and GitHub/GitLab**: Learn how to use Git for version control. Most organizations use Git for managing their codebases. Practice using platforms like GitHub or GitLab.\n\n### 6. Prepare Your Proposal\n- **Understand the Project**: Choose a project idea from the organization\u2019s ideas list or propose your own based on discussions with mentors.\n- **Draft Your Proposal**: Include your understanding of the project, a detailed plan of what you intend to do, and a timeline. Mention any relevant skills or previous contributions.\n- **Get Feedback**: Share your draft proposal with the community or mentors and incorporate their feedback.\n\n### 7. Time Management\n- **Set a Schedule**: Start preparing early. Set aside specific times each week for contributing to open source and refining your proposal.\n- **Stay Updated**: Keep an eye on the GSoC timeline and any updates from the organizations you are interested in.\n\n### 8. Application Submission\n- **Follow Guidelines**: Adhere strictly to the guidelines provided by GSoC and the specific organization.\n- **Submit Early**: Try to submit your proposal as early as possible. This gives you a chance to make last-minute improvements based on feedback.\n\n### 9. Prepare for the Coding Period\n- **Plan Ahead**: If selected, you\u2019ll need to manage your time effectively during the coding period. Plan how you\u2019ll balance your project with any other commitments.\n- **Stay Connected**: Keep in regular contact with your mentors and the community.\n\n### Additional Tips\n- **Networking**: Building relationships within the open source community can be beneficial. Attend meetups or online events if possible.\n- **Learning Resources**: Utilize online resources, tutorials, and documentation to quickly get up to speed with new technologies or tools required by your chosen project.\n\nBy following these steps, you\u2019ll be well-prepared to apply for GSoC 17. Good luck!",
